---
import DocsLayout from '../../../../layouts/DocsLayout.astro';
import Callout from '../../../../components/Callout.astro';
import Checklist from '../../../../components/Checklist.astro';
---

<DocsLayout title="Project 1: The static site" description="Direct AI to build a website and deploy it to a real URL.">
  <h1 class="mb-2">Project 1: The Static Site</h1>
  <p class="text-xl text-primary font-medium mb-6">"I can direct AI to build a website and deploy it to a real URL."</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll build</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">A professional business website for GreenScape Landscaping — a small landscaping company in Melbourne. Hero section, services grid, testimonials, about section, contact details. Single page, responsive, deployed to a live URL.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What's new (the +1)</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Everything. This is your first project. The terminal, VS Code, Git, Claude Code — all new. The product is deliberately simple so all your attention goes to learning the loop.</p>

  <Callout variant="info">
    <p class="text-sm"><strong>Why this project is deliberately simple:</strong> GreenScape is a single-page static website. No database, no backend, no user accounts. That's intentional — there's enough to learn just from the tools and the workflow.</p>
  </Callout>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What success looks like</h2>
  <Checklist items={[
    "A live URL you can share with anyone",
    "A site that matches the design specification (check with DevTools, not by eye)",
    "No features that aren't in the PRD (you caught every scope creep attempt)",
    "Confidence in the loop: branch → direct → verify → merge",
  ]} />

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">What you'll learn</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Direct Claude Code through the complete ticket cycle</li>
    <li>Verify AI output against a design specification using browser DevTools</li>
    <li>Catch anti-scope violations (AI adding features you didn't ask for)</li>
    <li>Deploy to a live URL using Netlify and handle deploy failures</li>
    <li>Read and act on AI code reviews (Claude self-review + Gemini)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Prerequisites</h2>
  <ul class="list-disc list-inside text-text-secondary space-y-2 text-sm mb-8">
    <li>Completed <a href="/web-dev/getting-started">Web Dev setup</a> (all tools installed and verified)</li>
  </ul>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Estimated time</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-8">2–4 days. 8 tickets.</p>

  <h2 class="mb-4 mt-10">Materials</h2>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-4">Every project follows the same planning sequence. In this project, all the planning has been done for you — so you can focus on learning the tools and the build loop. In later projects, you'll create each of these yourself by directing AI.</p>
  <p class="text-text-secondary mb-6">Read these in order before starting your first ticket:</p>

  <div class="space-y-4 mb-6">
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/prd">1. Product Requirements Document (PRD)</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The PRD defines <em>what</em> we're building. It starts with a client conversation — "I need a website for my landscaping business" — and turns that into structured requirements: features, acceptance criteria, user stories, and crucially, what we're <em>not</em> building (anti-scope). A good PRD is specific enough that someone could verify the finished product against it. In later projects, you'll direct AI to generate PRDs from client briefs — and your job will be catching what AI added that the client didn't ask for.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/design">2. Design specification</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The design spec defines <em>how the product looks and behaves</em>. In a real project, this might be a Figma file, wireframes, or a full design system — covering user flows, page layouts, responsive behaviour, and visual details like colours, typography, and spacing. For GreenScape, we've provided the design as a written spec with exact values you can verify in browser DevTools. The design spec is what separates "it works" from "it works <em>and</em> it's correct."</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-border bg-bg-subtle p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1 text-text-secondary">Architecture <span class="text-text-muted font-normal">(skipped in this project)</span></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The architecture document defines <em>how to build it</em> technically — database schema, API contracts, component structure, technology choices, and how the pieces fit together. You produce it from the PRD and design spec. Project 1 is a simple static site with no database or API, so we skip this step. From Project 2 onwards, you'll direct AI to generate the architecture, and your job will be catching over-engineering and missing dependencies.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/backlog">3. Backlog</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The backlog breaks the architecture (or in this case, the PRD) into an ordered list of tickets — small units of work, each with specific acceptance criteria. Tickets are ordered by dependency: you can't build the services section before the page layout exists. In later projects, you'll direct AI to produce the backlog from the architecture document. Each ticket becomes one cycle of the loop: branch → build → verify → merge.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/claude-md">4. CLAUDE.md</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The project memory file. This is the first thing that goes into your repository — before any code. Claude Code reads it at the start of every session, so it contains everything AI needs to stay consistent: tech stack, repo structure, anti-scope rules, engineering standards, and current project state. You derive it from the architecture and PRD. In later projects, you'll generate it from a template. Think of it as the briefing document for your AI developer.</p>
    </div>
    <div class="border-l-4 border-l-primary bg-primary-bg p-4 rounded-r-lg">
      <p class="font-semibold text-sm mb-1"><a href="/web-dev/projects/1/guide">5. Step-by-step guide</a></p>
      <p class="text-sm text-text-secondary">The build guide. This walks you through setting up VS Code, launching Claude, and completing your first ticket cycle. Follow it step by step for Ticket 1 and 2, then work through the remaining tickets independently — you'll know the loop by then.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
</DocsLayout>
